<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-a-sphere">
    <title>Surface Area of a Sphere</title>
    <p>
        The surface area of a sphere is the total area covering its curved outer surface.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Fun Activity Idea
            </p>
            <p>
                ðŸ”¹Use an orange or a ball and cover it with small square sticky notes.
            </p>
                
            <p>
               ðŸ”¹ Estimate how many squares fit over the sphereâ€™s surface.
             </p>
                <p>
                ðŸ”¹Then compare with other group members' results to the actual formula!
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <p>
        Formula for Surface Area of a Sphere
    </p>
    <p>
        Surface Area <m> = 4 \pi r^2</m> where rr is the radius of the sphere.
    </p>
    <p>
        The <m> = 4 \pi r^2</m> comes from integrating small patches over the sphereâ€™s curved surface. We can compare the sphere to how a sphere fits inside a cylinder of the same radius and height.
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
            Find the surface area of the following sphere (correct to 1 decimal place
        </p>  
        <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription> Sphere </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="sphere-example">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the main circle
                    \draw (0,0) circle (2);
                    
                    % Draw the dashed ellipse inside the circle
                    \draw[dashed] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.5);
                    \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.5);
                    
                    
                    % Draw and label the center point
                    \fill (0,0) circle (0.05);
                    \node[above right] at (0.5,0) {\small $r =7 cm$};
                    
                    % Draw the radius line
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image> 
       </statement> 
        <solution>
            <p>
              Surface area of a sphere = <m>4 \pi r^2</m>  
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4 \times \frac {22}{7}\times(7\text{cm})^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp  \frac{22}{7} \times 196\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp  22 \times 28 \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 616 \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution> 
    </example>  
    <example>
        <statement>
         <sidebyside>   
           <p> 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                A sphere has a radius of 14 cm.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        a) Find its total surface area.

                    </p>
                    <p>
                        b) If the sphere were covered with paint, how much area would be painted?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        c)If a second sphere has twice the radius, how does its surface area compare to the first sphere?
                    </p>

                </li>
            </ol>
           </p> 
           <image>
           <latex-image label="sphere-blue">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Draw the sphere
                \shade[ball color=blue!70] (0,0) circle (2cm);
                
                % Draw equator line
                \draw[dashed] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2cm and 0.5cm);
                \draw (-2,0) arc (180:0:2cm and 0.5cm);
                
                % Draw vertical meridian
                \draw[dashed] (0,-2) arc (-90:90:0.5cm and 2cm);
                \draw (0,2) arc (90:270:0.5cm and 2cm);
                
                % Draw radius
                \draw[thick, red] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[midway, above] {$r = 14$ cm};
                
                % Label sphere
                \node at (0,-2.5) {Sphere with radius \( r = 14cm \)};
            \end{tikzpicture}
           </latex-image>
           </image>
         </sidebyside>   
        </statement>

         <hint>
        <p>
        Remember, if the radius doubles, the surface area increases by 4 times (since  <m>(2r)^2 = 4 \pi r^2</m>.
      </p>
    </hint> 
    <solution>
        <p>
          a) Total Surface area. 
        </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4 \frac {22}{\cancel {7}}\times \cancel{14} \text{cm} \times 14 \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4 \times 22 \times 2  \text{cm} \times 14\text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp  4 \times 22 \times 28</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp  4 \times616 \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 2464\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                b) The <m>\textbf{area of the sphere painted}</m> would be the entire surface area.
            </p>
            <p>
                so the  Painted area =<m>2464\text{cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                c) If the radius is doubled i.e, </p>
                <p> ( <m>r = 14 \text{cm}+ 14\text {cm} = 28 \text{cm}</m>),</p>
                <p> the new surface area would be:
            </p>
            <p>
                 <md>
                    <mrow>\text{ New surface area} = \amp 4 \frac {22}{\cancel {7}}\times \cancel{28} \text{cm} \times 28 \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4 \times 22 \times 4  \text{cm} \times 28\text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp  4 \times 22 \times 112</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp  4 \times616 \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 9856\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
    </solution>
    </example>  
</subsection>